&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026. Prices below are the providers' advertised US consumer pricing at the time of writing; always confirm the current price on each provider's own site, as they change often.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; There is no single "cheapest" VIN check that is right for everyone, because the providers sell different things. A lot of the most useful information is free: NHTSA gives you recalls and crash-safety ratings, and the NICB's VINCheck gives you a theft and total-loss check, both at no cost. For an official title and brand history, an NMVTIS report from an approved provider is usually the cheapest paid option (often a few dollars). Budget history reports from around $8 to $20 add an easy-to-read summary and a valuation. Carfax and AutoCheck cost the most ($25 to $45) because they add proprietary accident and dealer-service records that the cheaper options do not have. The cheapest sensible approach for most buyers is to start with the free checks, then buy one paid report only on the car you are serious about.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;The full price comparison&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is what US drivers commonly pay in 2026 and what each option actually covers. "Accident" here means the detailed, reported accident history that comes from private dealer, body-shop and insurance feeds, which is different from the salvage and auction records that budget reports use as an indicator of major damage.&lt;/p&gt;

