&lt;h2&gt;Start with the free checks&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Before you pay anything, two official sources cover the safety basics for free:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NHTSA recalls and safety ratings.&lt;/strong&gt; At nhtsa.gov you can enter a VIN to see open safety recalls, and search by year, make and model for 5-star crash-test ratings. This is the official government source, and no paid report has better recall data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NICB VINCheck.&lt;/strong&gt; The National Insurance Crime Bureau offers a free VINCheck that flags whether a vehicle has been reported stolen (and not recovered) or declared a total loss by a participating insurer. It does not cover every insurer, but it is a genuinely free theft and total-loss screen.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For many private-party purchases, running these two free checks plus a careful in-person inspection removes the biggest risks at no cost. Where free checks fall short is a full title-brand and odometer history, which is where a paid report earns its money.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;The cheapest paid option: an official NMVTIS report&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;NMVTIS, the National Motor Vehicle Title Information System, is a federal database of title, brand, odometer and total-loss records. Consumers cannot buy from it directly; you buy an NMVTIS report from an approved provider listed at vehiclehistory.gov. These reports are often the cheapest paid checks available, sometimes only a few dollars, and they are the authoritative source for title brands such as salvage, junk, flood and rebuilt. They are typically plainer than a branded report and usually do not include a valuation or detailed accident history.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Budget history reports (about $8 to $20)&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A group of providers sell easy-to-read reports built from title, salvage, theft, auction and listing data, often bundled with a market value estimate. This tier includes VinAudit, ClearVin, EpicVIN, Bumper and CarWorthIt. They are much cheaper than Carfax and cover the essentials most buyers care about, but with an important limit: they do not have Carfax's or AutoCheck's proprietary accident and dealer-service records. Several of them use salvage-auction appearances as a proxy for major damage, which catches many wrecked cars but is not the same as a full accident report. CarWorthIt, for example, is $9.99 and pairs a valuation with title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction checks sourced from a licensed vehicle-data provider; like the others in this tier it does not include Carfax-style accident logs.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Why Carfax and AutoCheck cost more&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Carfax (about $45 for a single report, less per report in multi-packs) and AutoCheck (about $25 single, with a multi-report bundle that works out much cheaper per car) are the most expensive because they own data the others cannot buy. Over decades they built feeds from dealerships, repair shops, auctions and insurers, so a Carfax or AutoCheck report can show reported accidents and service visits that no budget or NMVTIS-only report will have. AutoCheck also adds an auction and scoring layer that dealers rely on. If a documented accident and service history genuinely matters for the car you are buying, this is the one thing worth paying more for.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;So what is actually cheapest for your situation?&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Just want recalls and a theft check?&lt;/strong&gt; Use NHTSA and NICB VINCheck for free.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Want to confirm the title is clean (salvage, flood, rebuilt)?&lt;/strong&gt; The cheapest reliable option is an official NMVTIS report from an approved provider, often only a few dollars.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Want an easy summary plus a value estimate?&lt;/strong&gt; A budget report in the $8 to $20 range such as VinAudit or CarWorthIt bundles the essentials with a valuation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Buying a higher-value car where accident history is critical?&lt;/strong&gt; Pay for Carfax or AutoCheck on that specific car; their proprietary accident and service data is the real reason to spend more.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The smartest, cheapest strategy is layered: free checks on every car on your shortlist, then a single paid report only on the finalist. Related reading: &lt;a href="/blog/is-carfax-worth-it"&gt;Is Carfax Worth It?&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="/blog/carfax-alternatives"&gt;Best Carfax Alternatives&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; You can check quite a lot about a car for free. NHTSA gives you open safety recalls and crash-test ratings by VIN, the NICB VINCheck flags reported theft and insurance total-loss records, a free VIN decoder shows the specs, and manufacturer sites confirm recall repair status. What you cannot get for free is a full title-brand and odometer history or a detailed accident report; those require a paid report or an official NMVTIS report, which usually costs only a few dollars. Below is exactly what each free tool covers and where free ends.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;What you can check for free&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Free tool&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;What it tells you&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Where&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;NHTSA recalls&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Open, unrepaired safety recalls by VIN&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;nhtsa.gov/recalls&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;NHTSA safety ratings&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;5-star crash-test ratings by year, make, model&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;nhtsa.gov&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;NICB VINCheck&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Reported theft (not recovered) and insurance total-loss (5 lookups / day)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;nicb.org&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;iSeeCars VIN report&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Market value, depreciation, theft and safety (no signup)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;iseecars.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;VIN decoder&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Year, make, model, engine, plant, body style&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;NHTSA vPIC and others&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;EPA fuel economy&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;MPG and estimated annual fuel cost&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;fueleconomy.gov&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Manufacturer recall lookup&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Recall status and open campaigns for that brand&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;the maker's owner site&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Step by step&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decode the VIN.&lt;/strong&gt; A free decoder (including NHTSA's vPIC) confirms the year, make, model, engine and where the car was built, so you can check the listing matches the car.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check open recalls.&lt;/strong&gt; Enter the VIN at nhtsa.gov to see any unrepaired safety recalls. This is the official source and it is free.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Run the NICB VINCheck.&lt;/strong&gt; At nicb.org, the free VINCheck flags whether the car was reported stolen and not recovered, or declared a total loss by a participating insurer. Coverage is not universal, but it is a real, free screen for two serious problems.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Look up running costs.&lt;/strong&gt; fueleconomy.gov shows the EPA MPG and an estimated annual fuel cost for that exact model.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Confirm recall repairs with the manufacturer.&lt;/strong&gt; The brand's owner site will show whether open recalls have been completed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Where free checks end&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Free tools do not give you a complete title history, every odometer reading, or a detailed accident record. Specifically, you will not see for free: the full list of title brands (salvage, junk, flood, rebuilt, lemon) across states, the ownership timeline, every reported mileage reading needed to catch rollback, or Carfax-style reported accidents and service visits. For the title, brand and odometer history, the cheapest option is an official NMVTIS report from an approved provider (listed at vehiclehistory.gov), often just a few dollars. For detailed accident and service history, Carfax or AutoCheck are the only sources, at a higher price.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;A note on "free VIN report" sites&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some sites advertise a "free VIN check" but only show the decoded specs and then ask you to pay for anything useful, or they show data you can already get free from NHTSA. That is not dishonest by itself, but be clear about what you are actually getting: if a site offers real title-brand or accident data for free, be skeptical, because that data is not free for the provider to obtain. CarWorthIt, for context, offers a genuinely free preview (specs, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs, all from the same public sources above) and charges only for the paid title, salvage, theft and valuation report.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Related reading: &lt;a href="/blog/cheapest-vin-check"&gt;Cheapest VIN Check Compared&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="/blog/how-to-check-car-recalls-vin"&gt;How to Check a Car for Recalls by VIN&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; The best Carfax alternative depends on what you need. AutoCheck is the closest like-for-like and cheaper, especially in its multi-report bundle. For the essentials at a low price, budget reports like VinAudit, ClearVin, EpicVIN, Bumper and CarWorthIt cover title, salvage, theft and odometer, usually with a value estimate. For an authoritative title and brand check on a budget, an official NMVTIS report from an approved provider is often the cheapest of all. And NHTSA and the NICB cover recalls, safety and theft for free. The one thing no alternative fully matches is Carfax's proprietary accident and dealer-service history.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;The alternatives at a glance&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Alternative&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Typical price&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Best for&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Main limitation vs Carfax&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;AutoCheck&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;About $25 single, cheaper in a bundle&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Closest full alternative, auction and score data&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Slightly thinner service history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Official NMVTIS report&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;About $2 to $13&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Authoritative title and brand check&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No accident detail or valuation&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;VinAudit&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;From about $10&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Cheap NMVTIS-based report with value&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No proprietary accident data&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;$9.99&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Cheap valuation plus title and salvage check&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No accident or service records&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;ClearVin&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;About $15&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Auction records and photos&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No dealer-service history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;EpicVIN&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;About $20 (less in packs)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Readable report with auction photos&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No dealer-service history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Bumper&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;About $20 to $25 / month&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Frequent buyers, sales history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Subscription, no full service history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;NHTSA + NICB&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Free&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Recalls, safety, theft and total-loss&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No title, odometer or accident detail&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;The honest limitation of every alternative&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It is worth being blunt about this, because it decides the whole choice: no cheaper service fully matches Carfax's reported accident and dealer-service history. Carfax and AutoCheck spent decades building private feeds from dealerships, repair shops, auctions and insurers. The budget and NMVTIS-based alternatives draw on title, salvage, theft, odometer and auction records instead, which is enough to catch a branded title, a rollback or a car that went through a salvage auction, but will not show a minor reported accident or a routine service trail. Choosing an alternative means accepting that trade-off in exchange for paying far less.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Which alternative should you pick?&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You want the closest thing to Carfax:&lt;/strong&gt; AutoCheck, especially the multi-report bundle if you are shopping several cars.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You mainly want to rule out a bad title:&lt;/strong&gt; an official NMVTIS report from an approved provider (vehiclehistory.gov), often the cheapest paid check.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You want a value estimate bundled in:&lt;/strong&gt; a budget report such as VinAudit or CarWorthIt, both around $10.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You want auction photos of prior damage:&lt;/strong&gt; ClearVin or EpicVIN.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You are checking many cars a month:&lt;/strong&gt; Bumper's subscription, or AutoCheck's bundle.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You want to spend nothing:&lt;/strong&gt; NHTSA for recalls and safety, NICB VINCheck for theft and total-loss.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Related reading: &lt;a href="/blog/is-carfax-worth-it"&gt;Is Carfax Worth It?&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="/blog/autocheck-vs-carfax"&gt;AutoCheck vs Carfax&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="/blog/cheapest-vin-check"&gt;Cheapest VIN Check Compared&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; Carfax and AutoCheck are the two premium US history reports, and both use proprietary data that budget reports lack. Carfax tends to have the deeper reported-accident and dealer-service history and the strongest brand recognition, so sellers and dealers often ask for it by name. AutoCheck, owned by Experian, is usually cheaper, leans on auction and title data, and adds a single AutoCheck score plus a multi-report bundle that makes checking several cars far cheaper per car. If you do not need proprietary accident data, cheaper alternatives and the free NHTSA and NICB checks will cover the essentials for much less.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

