&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Auction history&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Limited&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;A core strength&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Single score&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;No&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Yes (AutoCheck score)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Title, salvage, theft, odometer&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Yes&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Yes&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Brand recognition with sellers&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Highest&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;High&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Where Carfax is stronger&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Carfax generally has the most detailed reported-accident and service history, because its network of dealer and repair-shop feeds is the largest. It is also the name buyers and sellers know, so a "clean Carfax" is often used as a selling point, and some dealers provide one automatically. If you want the deepest service trail and the most recognized report, Carfax is the pick.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Where AutoCheck is stronger&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;AutoCheck, from Experian, is usually cheaper and is strong on auction history, which is useful for spotting a car that passed through a salvage or wholesale auction. Its single AutoCheck score gives a quick at-a-glance comparison between cars, which is why it is popular with dealers at auction. The big practical advantage for shoppers is the bundle: if you are checking many cars, AutoCheck's multi-report package drops the per-car cost well below a single Carfax report.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;When you do not need either&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Both are worth it when a documented accident and service history genuinely matters, usually on a higher-value car. But if you mainly want to confirm the title is clean, rule out theft, and check the odometer and recalls, you can do that far more cheaply. NHTSA covers recalls and safety for free, the NICB VINCheck covers theft and total-loss for free, an official NMVTIS report covers title brands for a few dollars, and budget reports like VinAudit or CarWorthIt bundle the essentials with a valuation for around $10. The catch is that these do not include Carfax or AutoCheck's proprietary accident and service data.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Related reading: &lt;a href="/blog/is-carfax-worth-it"&gt;Is Carfax Worth It?&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="/blog/carfax-alternatives"&gt;Best Carfax Alternatives&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="/blog/cheapest-vin-check"&gt;Cheapest VIN Check Compared&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; Checking a car for open safety recalls is free and takes about a minute. Enter the VIN at nhtsa.gov, which shows any unrepaired recalls from the official US government database, then confirm the repair status on the manufacturer's owner site. You never need to pay for recall data; paid history reports simply bundle the same free NHTSA information alongside other checks. Here is exactly how to do it and how to read the results.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Step by step&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Find the VIN.&lt;/strong&gt; It is on the lower corner of the windshield, the driver's door jamb, the title, and the insurance card. It is 17 characters.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Go to nhtsa.gov and enter the VIN.&lt;/strong&gt; NHTSA's recall lookup returns any open, unrepaired safety recalls for that specific vehicle, straight from the official database.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Read each recall.&lt;/strong&gt; Note the component (for example airbag, fuel system, brakes), the risk described, and whether a remedy is available.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Confirm the repair on the manufacturer site.&lt;/strong&gt; Each automaker has an owner or recall page where the same VIN shows whether the recall work has been completed. Open recalls are usually repaired free at a franchised dealer.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ask the seller for proof.&lt;/strong&gt; If a recall is open, ask the seller to have it fixed before purchase, or use it in your price negotiation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Where to check recalls&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Source&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;What it shows&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;Cost&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;NHTSA (nhtsa.gov)&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Open, unrepaired safety recalls by VIN&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Free&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Manufacturer owner site&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Recall status and whether repairs were completed&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Free&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Paid history reports&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;The same NHTSA recall data, bundled with other checks&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Paid&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Things to know about recall results&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;NHTSA shows open recalls only.&lt;/strong&gt; If a recall was already repaired, it usually drops off the VIN lookup, so a clean result can mean either no recalls or all recalls completed. Confirm with the manufacturer if you are unsure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recalls are repaired free.&lt;/strong&gt; Safety recall repairs are done at no cost at a franchised dealer, regardless of who owns the car, though very old recalls can occasionally fall outside coverage.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recalls are not the same as complaints or investigations.&lt;/strong&gt; A recall is an official action. NHTSA also lists owner complaints and open investigations, which are useful context but not the same thing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Paid VIN reports, including CarWorthIt, include the NHTSA recall data as part of a wider report, but the recall information itself is the same free government data you can look up yourself at nhtsa.gov. Related reading: &lt;a href="/blog/free-vin-check"&gt;How to Check a VIN for Free&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="/blog/cheapest-vin-check"&gt;Cheapest VIN Check Compared&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last updated 2026.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Short answer:&lt;/strong&gt; Checking a used car well comes down to three layers. First, the free checks: decode the VIN, look up open recalls and safety ratings at NHTSA, and run the NICB VINCheck for theft and total-loss. Second, a history report to confirm the title is clean, the odometer is honest, and, on a pricier car, the accident record. Third, an in-person inspection and test drive, ideally with a mechanic. Do the free checks on every car on your shortlist, buy one report on the finalist, and never skip the physical inspection. Here is the full checklist.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Layer 1: the free checks (every car)&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decode the VIN&lt;/strong&gt; to confirm the year, make, model and engine match the listing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check open recalls and safety ratings&lt;/strong&gt; at nhtsa.gov.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Run the NICB VINCheck&lt;/strong&gt; at nicb.org for reported theft and insurance total-loss.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Look up running costs&lt;/strong&gt; (MPG and fuel cost) at fueleconomy.gov.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Layer 2: the history report (the finalist)&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Once a car passes the free checks, a paid report confirms the paperwork:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Title brands:&lt;/strong&gt; salvage, junk, flood, rebuilt or lemon markers that a clean-looking title can hide across state lines.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Odometer history:&lt;/strong&gt; multiple readings over time to catch a rollback.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theft and total-loss&lt;/strong&gt; records.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Accident history&lt;/strong&gt; on higher-value cars, where Carfax or AutoCheck's proprietary data is worth the extra cost.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Match the report to the car. An official NMVTIS report (a few dollars) or a budget report like VinAudit or CarWorthIt (around $10) covers title, salvage, theft and odometer, and often a valuation. Carfax or AutoCheck cost more but add the detailed accident and service history. See &lt;a href="/blog/cheapest-vin-check"&gt;Cheapest VIN Check Compared&lt;/a&gt; to pick.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Layer 3: the inspection and test drive&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;table&gt;
&lt;thead&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;th&gt;Check&lt;/th&gt;&lt;th&gt;What you are looking for&lt;/th&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Panel gaps and paint&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Mismatched paint or uneven gaps suggest prior accident repair&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Tires&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Uneven wear can mean alignment or suspension problems&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Fluids&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Milky oil, low or burnt fluid, or leaks&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Electronics&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Warning lights, windows, locks, infotainment, cameras&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Test drive&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;Cold start, firm acceleration, braking, steering pull, transmission shifts&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;Mechanic inspection&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;A pre-purchase inspection is the single best money you can spend on a used car&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A history report and a test drive cover different risks. The report catches paperwork problems you cannot see; the inspection catches mechanical and repair problems the paperwork will never show. A clean report with no inspection, or an inspection with no report, both leave a gap.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="not-prose"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Check a VIN:&lt;/strong&gt; you can run any US VIN on &lt;a href="/#check"&gt;CarWorthIt&lt;/a&gt; for a free preview (specifications, open recalls, safety ratings and running costs), with an optional paid report that adds title, salvage, theft and salvage-auction records plus a market valuation.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Use what you find to negotiate&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Every issue is leverage. An open recall, a high insurance cost, a worn tire set, or a car that sat through a salvage auction are all reasons to ask for a lower price or a repair before purchase. The point of checking thoroughly is not only to walk away from a bad car, but to buy a good one for less.&lt;/p&gt;

